Typhoid fever - Australia ex Papua New Guinea? (02) 990609220221
[1
Date: Wed, 09 Jun 1999 21:58:32 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: http://www.abc.net.au/news/1999/06/item19990610012955_1.htm

Health authorities are working through passenger lists to contact people
who took a cruise to New Guinea and have been exposed to typhoid. Four
people have been confirmed to have the highly-contagious disease and four
more are suspected to have contracted it from a meal taken at a hotel on
the way to the Kokoda Trail. They were on the P&O liner Fair Princess
which left Cairns on May 12.
Dr Graeme Rouch, who chairs the Australian and New Zealand Communicable
Disease Network, says typhoid is readily treated with antibiotics and is
rarely fatal in Australia. "It's an insidious disease. If it's treated in
the first week the symptoms
don't get too severe," Dr Rouch said. "As the disease progresses without
treatment, they start to get very confused and eventually end up moribund."
Ken Adams from Newcastle, who was a passenger, says he spoke to a number of
people on board who reported feeling ill and a petition was taken up among
those who went on the Kokoda trail. "They said they were in bed sick and
the doctor on the ship told them that they had food poisoning from the
Kokoda trail and they were in bed for a couple of days," Mr Adams said.
"I must say any food that P&O prepared was fine it was just what was
prepared on the island that was the problem."
*******
[2
Date: Thu, 10 Jun 1999 18:39:44 +0800
From: Len Moaven <moaven@bigpond.com.au>

For those interested in counting heads, we have another case in Perth today
(10 Jun 1999) which we picked up with blood cultures (three positive
sets!). This 48 year old lady who had been on the boat presented to her
[physician after seeing the story on the news. She has fever, general
malaise, rash, neutropenia and a transaminitis.
--
Dr Len Moaven FRCPA
Clinical Microbiologist
