[3
Date: Thu, 10 Jun 1999 08:59:03 -0700
From: David Dassey <ddassey@dhs.co.la.ca.us>

The reports mention an array of symptoms that are not typical of typhoid
fever: "120 of the 900 passengers on board had been afflicted with severe
diarrhoea, abdominal cramping and vomiting, or a range of other symptoms.
"Has the report of three passengers with _S. typhi_ been confirmed by
public health officials? The incubation period for typhoid is generally 1
week or more, although it can be shorter with larger doses of organisms.
Was this cruise out for an extended period, or is some other enteric
infection with a shorter incubation period (viral, other bacterial) more
likely?
--
David E. Dassey MD
Acute Communicable Disease Control
Los Angeles County Department of Health Services
313 N. Figueroa St. #212
Los Angeles, CA 90012
e-mail: ddassey@dhs.co.la.ca.us
[My reading of this and prior postings leads to the conclusion that there
are currently 4 confirmed cases. Dr. Dassey has a point that there may be
another form of food poisoning superimposed on this outbreak of typhoid. -
